#. type: Title ===
#: documentation/content/en/books/handbook/basics/_index.adoc:344
#, fuzzy, no-wrap
msgid "Managing Accounts"
msgstr ""
"管理账户\n"
"\n"
"== Introduction\n"
"\n"
"Managing accounts is an important task in the computer field. It involves creating, configuring, and maintaining user accounts on different systems and platforms. This process ensures that users have the necessary access and permissions to perform their tasks while ensuring the security and integrity of the system.\n"
"\n"
"== User Accounts\n"
"\n"
"A user account is a unique identifier assigned to an individual or system entity to access a computer system or network. User accounts can be classified into different types, such as local accounts, domain accounts, and service accounts.\n"
"\n"
"=== Local Accounts\n"
"\n"
"Local accounts are created on a specific computer system and are limited to that system only. They are commonly used for personal computers or standalone servers, where there is no central authentication system.\n"
"\n"
"=== Domain Accounts\n"
"\n"
"Domain accounts, on the other hand, are created and managed by a centralized authentication system known as a domain controller. These accounts can be used to access multiple systems within a network, providing a centralized and secure management approach.\n"
"\n"
"=== Service Accounts\n"
"\n"
"Service accounts are specialized accounts used by services or applications to access network resources. They are created for specific purposes and have predetermined privileges and permissions.\n"
"\n"
"== Account Management Tasks\n"
"\n"
"Account management involves several key tasks that ensure the smooth operation and security of user accounts.\n"
"\n"
"=== Account Creation\n"
"\n"
"Creating a new account involves providing the necessary information, such as username, password, and account type. This process can be performed through the user interface or command-line tools.\n"
"\n"
"=== Account Configuration\n"
"\n"
"Account configuration includes setting up various parameters and options associated with user accounts, such as password policies, access rights, and group memberships.\n"
"\n"
"=== Account Maintenance\n"
"\n"
"Account maintenance tasks include activities such as password resets, account lockouts, and account deletions. Regular monitoring and updates are essential to ensure the security and usability of user accounts.\n"
"\n"
"== Conclusion\n"
"\n"
"Managing accounts is a critical aspect of computer administration. By properly creating, configuring, and maintaining user accounts, organizations can ensure secure access to their systems and maintain the integrity of their networks."

#. type: delimited block = 4
#: documentation/content/en/books/handbook/basics/_index.adoc:349
